      <body>
        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0457.jpg" n="part3_p065.jpg" xml:id="img_0065" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part3_p065.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_65_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>dʼune
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>-aus¬
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>Then let us go to community. I will go to this further on more fully, but the individual
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>personality has become the LONELY personality, and finally, since loneliness cannot be stood,
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>"the lonely crowd," who goes into the group, into the trowd, where he tries to overcome his
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>loneliness but is not able to, and so he returns, or very often feels even more lovely in the crowd,
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>and what isLacking, what former period had—and what I Boicated when I spoke of contemplation
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>of nature-that is solitude. Without solitude, man iseneopled. And the idea of personality has
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>very much to do with the crippling of man on the basis of his being without solution.
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/>The further problems connected with this relation, I will discuss in connection with social others
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_1_tl_11" n="N011"/>I now come to one’s self, namely the cutting off of one's self. Here I want to jump to
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_65_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>one of the sections which I have under No. 17, family and sex relationships. In the idea of
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>personality, not only the relationship to nature, and the eros to the objects of our work—and therefore
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>to the work itself--but also the relationship to ourselves insofar as something is not brought into the
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>conscious willing,éeiding tenter, is cut off. The concept of self-controlling is certainly a concept
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>which is needed in many special situation; he who has not self-control can never become a Ma¬
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>personality, and that belong to the formation of man to become this. But if he pays for this,
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>being a Maentered personality, the price of cutting himself off from the vital dimension of his being,
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_65_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>from that which today is predominantly called the unconscious, or the subconscious or the vital,
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>then that Nenomenon comes into existence which we call repression. Repression can
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>last for a certain time. It is often a matter of one or two deserations. But it cannot last forever
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>de cette
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>de votre beau moi
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>Votre très-hier vieusement les
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>dʼun autre
               <lb facs="#facs_65_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>Monsieur
            </p>
            
        </div>
